'''Nikolaos Loukanis''' was a 16th-century [[Greeks|Greek]] [[Renaissance humanism|Renaissance humanist]]. He worked in [[Venice]] where in 1526 he produced a translation of [[Homer|Homer's]] [[Iliad]] into [[modern Greek]] which is credited as one of the first literary texts published in [[Modern Greek]] (as most contemporary Greek scholars wrote in the [[Koine]]).<ref>Hans Georg Beck, Manoussos Manoussacas, Agostino Pertusi , ''Venezia, Centro Di Mediazione Tra Oriente E Occidente, Secoli XV-XVI'', 1977, p.457</ref><ref>Nigel Guy Wilson, Encyclopedia Of Ancient Greece, 2006, p.367</ref><ref>[http://www.elia.org.gr/default.fds?langid=2&pagecode=16.05.02 ELIA reference to Loukanis' first publication in modern Greek]</ref>
